<stack-static>
    <statement><p><p>A right-angled triangle has side lengths of <m>{6}</m> cm, <m>{8}</m> cm, and <m>{10}</m> cm.</p>

<p>This triangle undergoes an enlargement with a scale factor of <alert><m>k = {-0.5}</m></alert>.</p>
<ol>
    <li>Calculate the perimeter of the original triangle. <br/>
        <fillin characters="6" name="ans1"/> cm
    </li>
    <li>Calculate the perimeter of the image triangle after the enlargement. <br/>
        <fillin characters="6" name="ans2"/> cm 
    </li>
</ol></p></statement>
    <solution><p><h3> Worked Solution</h3>

<alert>Step 1: Perimeter of the Original Triangle</alert>
<p>The perimeter is the sum of all side lengths:</p>
<md>
<mrow>P_{\text{original}} \amp = {6} + {8} + {10}</mrow>
<mrow>\amp = \mathbf{{24} \text{ cm}}</mrow>
</md>

<alert>Step 2: Understanding the Effect of a Negative Scale Factor</alert>
<p>A negative scale factor, such as <m>k = {-0.5}</m>, indicates that the image is inverted and on the opposite side of the center of enlargement. However, physical lengths cannot be negative.</p>
<p>When calculating the dimensions of the image, we multiply the original lengths by the absolute value of the scale factor (<m>|k|</m>):</p>
<me> \text{Image Length} = \text{Original Length} \times |k| </me>

<alert>Step 3: Perimeter of the Image</alert>
<p>We apply the scale factor to the original perimeter:</p>
<md>
<mrow>P_{\text{image}} \amp = P_{\text{original}} \times |{-0.5}|</mrow>
<mrow>\amp = {24} \times {0.5}</mrow>
<mrow>\amp = {12.0} \text{ cm}</mrow>
</md></p></solution>
    <answer><p><m>24</m></p></answer>
    <answer><p><m>12.0</m></p></answer>
</stack-static>